        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "— Spitting in the face ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "was the greatest contempt and disgrace which could possibly be shown. See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 12:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Buffeting, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or striking a person with the fist on the temples, was esteemed one of the most disgraceful punishments by the Greeks, from whom the Romans might have adopted it. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Smiting with the open palm of their hands, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "was such a dishonour as none but a slave ought to endure. “Because Matthew here says, that they who condemned Jesus ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "spit in his face, and buffeted him: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 14:65",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", mentions the indignities which the servants in particular put upon him; it appears that he was smitten, blindfolded, and buffeted even by some of the council; who, to ridicule him for having pretended to be the great prophet foretold by Moses, bade him exercise his prophetical gift in guessing who it was that struck him; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Prophesy unto us, thou Christ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— It was hardly possible for those miscreants to invent any thing more expressive of the contempt in which they held our Lord’s pretensions to be the Messiah. Thus was the Judge of the world placed at the bar of his own creatures, falsely accused by the witnesses, unjustly condemned by his judges, and insulted by all. Yet, because it was agreeable to the end of his coming, he patiently submitted, though he could with a frown have made his judges, his accusers, and those who had him in custody, all to drop down dead in a moment, or to shrivel into nothing.” — Macknight.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
