        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the former word presumably pointing to some Sanhedrists. In Mt. the connection suggests Sanhedrists alone. Incredible that they should condescend to so unworthy proceedings, one is inclined to say. Yet it was night, there was intense dislike and they might feel they did God service by disgracing a pretender. Hence the invitation to the would-be christ to prophesy (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "προφήτευσον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") who smote him when he was struck behind the back or blindfolded (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 14:65",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Thus did they fill up the early hours of the morning on that miserable night. Sceptical critics, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "e.g.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Brandt, p. 69, also Holtz., H. C., suggest that the colouring of this passage is drawn from O. T. texts, such as Micah 4:14 (Sept[146] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
